m of the ''Wayside Flower'' fishing for shellfish out of Bridlington in 1962]\n*[http://www.bridlingtonharbour.com/bridlington-sailing-coble-preservation-society/ Bridlington Coble Preservation Society]\n*[https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/heritage/how-the-tide-turned-for-hull-s-fishing-dock-1-7636913 St Andrews Dock, Hull - fish dock connected to NER later LNER]\n\n{{The Yorkshire coast}}\n{{fishing history}}\n{{fisheries and fishing}}\n\n[[Category:Fishing in England]]\n[[Category:History of fishing]]\n[[Category:Traditional boats]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|History of sea fishing in Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{infobox fishery\n| image             = Bridlington Harbour. - geograph.org.uk - 401792.jpg\n| caption           = Fishing Boats Moored in [[Bridlington]] Harbour\n| Hide header       = \n| Header caption    = \n| coastline         = [[Yorkshire Coast]]\n| EEZ area          = United Kingdom\n| EEZ PP            = \n| continental shelf = United Kingdom\n| lake area         = \n| river area        = \n| land area         = \n| MPA area          = Runswick Bay<br>Holderness Inshore<br>Holderness Offshore\n| employment        = 6,500 (2017){{#tag:ref|Official designation is ''Yorkshire and the Humber'', so statistics will include the town of Grimsby.<ref name=\"RB\">{{cite web |last1=Ares |first1=Elena |last2=Rhodes |first2=Chris |last3=Ward |first3=Matthew |title=The UK Fishing Industry |url=http://researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk/documents/CDP-2017-0256/CDP-2017-0256.pdf |website=researchbriefings.files.parliament.uk |accessdate=16 February 2020 |page=5 |format=PDF |date=December 2017}}</ref>|name=YAH|group=note}}\n| fishing fleet     = \n| landing sites     = {{Plainlist|\n*[[Bridlington]]\n*[[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]]\n*[[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]]\n*[[Whitby]]\n}}\n| consumption       = \n| fisheries GDP     = \u00a316&nbsp;million (2017)\n| export value      = \n| import value      = \n}}\nThe '''Yorkshire coast fishery''' has been a mainstay of the economy of the [[Yorkshire and Humber region]] for centuries. The fishing industry has been in decline since the mid to late 20th century due to many factors such as labour problems, fishing quotas and decommissioning schemes. Historically, the ports at [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] and [[Whitby]] have been important locations for the landing and processing of fish and shellfish. This industry continues today at both locations though on a smaller scale, and both have fish processing industries too. [[Bridlington]] has now become the largest shellfish port in [[Europe]], regularly exporting its catch abroad, mostly to European countries.\n\nThe ceremonial counties of the [[East Riding of Yorkshire|East]] and [[North Riding of Yorkshire|North Ridings of Yorkshire]] had many ports both small and large where sea catch was landed.{{#tag:ref|The traditional definition of the Yorkshire region is the {{convert|114|mi}} of coastline between the mouth of the [[River Tees]] and the [[Humber Estuary]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mitchell |first1=Barry |title=Exploring the Yorkshire coast |date=1984 |publisher=Dalesman |location=Clapham |isbn=0-85206-764-X |page=5 |edition=4 |chapter=Introduction}}</ref> As such, the sea fishing industry was confined to the East and North Ridings of Yorkshire, though catches could be landed in [[Goole]] which was historically in the [[West Riding of Yorkshire|West Riding]]. Post 1974, some of the ports along the coast around [[Redcar]] are now classified as being in [[Redcar and Cleveland]].|name=|group=note}}\n\nThe Yorkshire region is the second largest fishing industry in the United Kingdom (after Scotland) in terms of the number of people who work in the industry. Fish is landed commercially at four ports in Yorkshire; Bridlington, Hull, [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]] and Whitby\n\n==History==\nUp until the 1840s, the fisheries were landing catches that supplied only their immediate area;{{sfn|Uglow|1991|p=180}} Scarborough, for example, saw an increase in its fishing fleet from 130 ships in 1840 to 800 ships in 1860. The rise in the number of boats and the increased catch, was down to the coming of the railways, which allowed fresh fish to be transported many miles inland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scarborough Maritime Heritage Centre {{!}} History of the Scarborough Fishing Industry |url=http://www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk/article.php?article=149 |website=www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk |accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref> The transport of fish was an important business for the railways, and in 1922, the tonnages of fish transported by the railway network from the Yorkshire ports was as follows;\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Station name\n!Tonnage\n!Totals\n!Notes\n|-\n|{{rws|Staithes}}\n|{{convert|203|tonne}}\n|{{convert|203|tonne}}\n|{{sfn|Hoole|1985|p=190}} Small tonnages were usually sent in vans attached to passenger trains, which were then shunted onto larger freight trains in Whitby or Scarborough<ref>{{cite book |last1=Hoole |first1=K |title=Railways of the North York Moors : a pictorial history |date=1983 |publisher=Dalesman Books |location=Clapham |isbn=0852067313 |page=[https://archive.org/details/railwaysofnorthy0000hool/page/55 55] |url=https://archive.org/details/railwaysofnorthy0000hool/page/55 }}</ref>\n|-\n|{{rws|Whitby}}\n|{{convert|182|tonne}}\n|{{convert|385|tonne}}\n|{{sfn|Hoole|1985|p=196}}\n|-\n|{{rws|Scarborough}}\n|{{convert|7,791|tonne}}\n|{{convert|8,176|tonne}}\n|Most of the fish traffic was loaded at [[Gallows Close goods yard]]{{sfn|Hoole|1985|p=186}}\n|-\n|{{rws|Filey}} \n|{{convert|164|tonne}}\n|{{convert|8,340|tonne}}\n|{{sfn|Hoole|1985|p=164}}\n|-\n|{{rws|Flamborough}}\n|{{convert|386|tonne}}\n|{{convert|8,726|tonne}}\n|{{sfn|Hoole|1985|p=164}}\n|-\n|{{rws|Bridlington}}\n|{{convert|310|tonne}}\n|{{convert|9,036|tonne}}\n|{{sfn|Hoole|1985|p=155}}\n|-\n|{{rws|Hull Paragon}}\n|{{convert|86,910|tonne}}\n|{{convert|95,946|tonne}}\n|{{sfn|Hoole|1985|p=171}}\n|-\n|}\nThe forwarding of fish from Hull also meant that it developed a lucrative fish market with buyers from many inland places needing their catch taken inland as it was a perishable commodity.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Finn |first1=M W |title=Economic and Social History of Britain Since 1700 |date=1975 |publisher=Macmillan Publishers Limited |location=London |isbn=978-1-349-00025-8 |page=109 |chapter=9: Transport}}</ref>\n\nSome of the first experiments in deep-sea trawling were conducted off the Holderness Coast at Flamborough in the early part of the 19th century.{{sfn|HCF|2011|p=12}} However, until the days of large fishing trawlers in the 20th century, the most common boat in service across Yorkshire (and the north east coast) was the [[Coble]]. The design of the coble is a basic one with a short plank laid horizontally instead of a keel and a flat bottom on the boat. The flat bottom allowed the coble to be berthed almost anywhere as it did not need extensive harbour facilities; most cobles where simply hauled onto the beaches when not in use.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Allen |first1=Irene |last2=Todd |first2=Alan |title=Filey : a Yorkshire fishing town : Filey fishing families over the last two centuries |date=1985 |publisher=Allen & Todd |isbn=0-948781-00-9 |page=24}}</ref>\n\nThe coble (pronounced ''cobble'') has been on the eastern coast of Britain for a 1,000 years<ref>{{cite news |title=Antique coble gets face lift |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/humberside/hi/people_and_places/history/newsid_8222000/8222396.stm |accessdate=4 August 2019 |work=BBC News |date=26 August 2009}}</ref> and has a ribbed look (known as ''clinker built'') where the planks, made from larch wood, overlap each other.<ref>{{cite news |title=Reviving the ancient skill of coble-building |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/reviving-the-ancient-skill-of-coble-building-1-6714103 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=7 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Scarborough Maritime Heritage Centre {{!}} Yorkshire's last traditional sailing fishing coble |url=http://www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk/article.php?article=10 |website=www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref> The coble fell out of favour after the [[First World War]] as they were sail boats, and motorised fishing vessels took their place,<ref name=\"BFP\"/> although some cobles have had engines fitted.<ref>{{cite news |title=Return of the \u2018little ships\u2019 that brought fish back to Bridlington |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/our-region/north-yorkshire-moors-and-coast/return-of-the-little-ships-that-brought-fish-back-to-bridlington-1-9718475 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=18 April 2019}}</ref> There are now several preservation movements dedicated to the history of the coble.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cobles to descend on harbour for festival |url=https://www.bridlingtonfreepress.co.uk/news/cobles-to-descend-on-harbour-for-festival-1-7824560 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |work=Bridlington Free Press |date=1 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Name Three Brothers {{!}} National Historic Ships |url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/2463/three-brothers |website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk |accessdate=4 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nOne tradition that still exists is that of the [[Guernsey (clothing)|Gansey]].<ref>{{cite web |title=What's a gansey? |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/northyorkshire/content/articles/2007/09/17/fishermens_ganseys_feature.shtml |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref> These are woollen jumpers that fishermen wore whilst at sea to keep them warm and deflect sea spray. The tradition in the Yorkshire ports was that each one had a different design. This was practical rather than sartorial; if a body of a fisherman was washed ashore his port of origin could be easily identified.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Freeman |first1=Sarah |title=How one Robin Hood\u2019s Bay firm is knitting a future in heritage fishing jumpers |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/how-one-robin-hood-s-bay-firm-is-knitting-a-future-in-heritage-fishing-jumpers-1-9055787/ |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=10 March 2018|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nThe port of Whitby was noted as being the main port for the landing of herring. The herring fishery extended from {{convert|3|mi}} to {{convert|7|mi}} east of Whitby, though some boats went fishing as far out as {{convert|60|mi}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=England's Historic Seascapes: Scarborough to Hartlepool |url=https://archaeologydataservice.ac.uk/archives/view/ehsscarborough_eh_2007/fisheries.cfm |website=Archaeology Data Service |accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref> Not all of the boats came from Whitby, or indeed from Yorkshire; fishing boats came from as far afield as Scotland, [[East Anglia]] and [[Cornwall]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Point 5 - The fish quay |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/northyorkshire/content/articles/2005/04/04/coast05walks_stage5.shtml |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=3 December 2019}}</ref> Whitby still has a traditional [[kipper]] smokehouse, though most of the herring comes from Norwegian waters.<ref>{{cite news |title=We visited Whitby\u2019s last traditional kipper smokehouse |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/we-visited-whitby-s-last-traditional-kipper-smokehouse-1-9570481 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=2 February 2019|url-access=limited}}</ref> As a side venture to the herring fishery, sport fishing for tuna was carried out until the early 1950s, when the tuna stopped coming due to the overfishing of herring and mackerel.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coble in rare tuna catch off Whitby |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/coble-in-rare-tuna-catch-off-whitby-1-4673537 |accessdate=3 December 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=23 June 2012|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nThe inherent danger of fishing at sea is borne out by the fact that between 1808 and 1970, over 400 ships were lost off the Yorkshire coast. At least 74 of these (19%) were lost due to military action during the [[First World War|First]] and [[Second World War|Second World War's]].{{#tag:ref|Fishing boats as casualties of both world wars were lost by being struck by torpedoes, engaged by enemy aircraft, attacked deliberately by U-Boats, or sunk after hitting mines.{{sfn|Godfrey|1974|pp=61\u201371}}<ref>{{cite news |last1=Airey |first1=Tom |title=The 'gentlemanly massacre' of WW1 ships |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-37424081 |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=30 September 2016}}</ref>|name=Sinkings|group=note}} Many fishing vessels were lost after the First World War when their nets brought sea mines onto the ship; in 1919, three Hull trawlers were lost this way, similarly, three trawlers working out of Scarborough were lost in 1920, one of which went down with all hands.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Robinson |first1=Robb |title=Fishermen, the fishing industry and the Great War at sea : a forgotten history? |date=2019 |publisher=Liverpool University Press |location=Liverpool |isbn=978-1-78694-175-6 |pages=170\u2013171 |chapter=8: The Aftermath}}</ref>\n\nThroughout the 1960s, the crab fishery on the Yorkshire coast represented 40% of the catch landed in England and Wales.{{sfn|Edwards|1967|p=1}} Cobles landed the catch at Redcar, Staithes, Whitby, Scarborough, Filey, Flamborough and Bridlington.{{sfn|Edwards|1967|p=10}}\n\nThe fishermen who worked out of the Port of Hull suffered during the [[Cod Wars]] of the 1960s and 1970s. Trawlermen who lost their jobs as a result of the agreement between the United Kingdom and Iceland did not receive redundancy payments, though some were entitled to compensation after an intervention by [[Alan Johnson MP]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ledger |first1=John |title=How the Cod War of 40 years ago left a Yorkshire community devastated |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/our-region/east-yorkshire/how-the-cod-war-of-40-years-ago-left-a-yorkshire-community-devastated-1-7636401 |accessdate=27 July 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=21 December 2015}}</ref> Fishermen working out of Hull (and Grimsby) were given incentives such as being partners in the boats they operated on which regulated supply of fish and kept the market price of the commodity stable. However, this in turn led to the smaller ports landing less fish as the buyers went to either Hull or [[Grimsby]] to obtain fish on a regular basis because of the guaranteed supply.{{sfn|Uglow|1991|p=181}}\n\nDue to overfishing, a European scheme to curtail the amount of fish landed led to a decommissioning scheme throughout the 1990s and into the early part of the 21st century.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hatcher |first1=Aaron C |title=Producers' organizations and devolved fisheries management in the United Kingdom: Collective and individual quota systems |journal=Marine Policy |date=November 1997 |volume=21 |issue=6 |pages=519\u2013533 |doi=10.1016/S0308-597X(97)00019-5}}</ref> Fishermen and women were encouraged to scrap their boats and forfeit their licences in return for a government grant to compensate them.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kravanja |first1=Milan |last2=Shapiro |first2=Ellen |title=World fishing fleets : an analysis of distant-water fleet operations, past, present, future. Vol. V, The Baltic States, the Commonwealth of Independent States, Eastern Europe |date=1993 |publisher=National Marine Fisheries Service, National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |location=Silver Spring |page=159|oclc=31596945}}</ref> Money awarded to applicants fluctuated with demand and specific food fish (at times, only the [[Whitefish (fisheries term)|whitefish]] boats were needed to sign up for the scheme.)<ref>{{cite news |title=Fishing pay-off scheme opens |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/scotland/1518029.stm |accessdate=17 February 2020 |work=BBC News |date=31 August 2001}}</ref> In 2001, the [[UK Government]] were paying \u00a31,684 per gross tonne of vessel.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trawlers set to be scrapped in fishing scheme |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/trawlers-set-to-be-scrapped-in-fishing-scheme-1-2409725 |accessdate=17 February 2020 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=12 December 2001 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Whitby through the Lobster Pots.jpg|thumb|Whitby through the Lobster Pots]]\nBy the start of the 21st century, the fishing industry in Yorkshire was using five main methods of catching fish;<ref>{{cite web |title=Yorkshire's fishing industry today |url=https://www.northyorkmoors.org.uk/visiting/eat/fish-fillet-feast/yorkshires-fishing-industry-today |website=North York Moors National Park |accessdate=26 July 2019}}</ref>\n*Potting\n*Gill netting\n*Trawling\n*Scallop dredging\n*Intertidal netting.\n\nOn the section  of the Yorkshire coast between Flamborough Head and [[Spurn Point]] (the Holderness Coast), the fishery now only lands crab and lobster.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cash awarded for fishing industry |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-15886639 |accessdate=26 July 2019 |work=BBC News |date=25 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nAfter the public vote for Brexit, a government sponsored report stated that over 6,500 people throughout Yorkshire were directly involved in the fishing industry. This placed the [[Yorkshire and Humber region]] as second only in size to Scotland, which is the largest fishing industry sector in the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"RB\"/> Additionally, the post-Brexit scenario could include fishing fleets operating from Yorkshire ports being denied the rights to fish in waters off of Norway and Iceland.<ref>{{cite news |title=State-of-the-art Hull trawler could end up on quayside in event of no deal |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/state-of-the-art-hull-trawler-could-end-up-on-quayside-in-event-of-no-deal-1-9983427 |accessdate=9 September 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=9 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nCommercially, fish is landed at only four Yorkshire ports (Bridlington, Hull, Scarborough and Whitby) though not all fish landed at these ports are from fleets registered at those ports. Additionally, the port at Whitby has suffered from a lack of investment in its infrastructure, so much so, that some fishing boats registered at Whitby travel to the dock at [[North Shields]], {{convert|50|mi}} to the north to unload their catch.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fishermen move north for profit |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-tyne-13202874 |accessdate=1 January 2020 |work=BBC News |date=27 April 2011}}</ref> Even so, the catch landed in Yorkshire represented a value of over \u00a316&nbsp;million in 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shellfish catches lead the way for Yorkshire harbours |url=https://fishingnews.co.uk/features/shellfish-catches-lead-the-way-for-yorkshire-harbours/ |accessdate=1 January 2020 |work=Fishing News |date=29 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nWhitby has the only ''fishing school'' in the United Kingdom, which aims to afford training to young apprentices in the various fishing trades on offer around the coasts of Britain.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Carr |first1=Flora |title=How a local school in Whitby hopes to save Britain's fishing industry |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/2017/10/10/local-school-whitby-hopes-save-britains-fishing-industry/ |accessdate=1 January 2020 |work=The Telegraph |date=10 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Ports==\nDuring the 18th, 19th and 20th centuries, the following locations were known as having fishing boats working from them.{{sfn|Freethy|2012|p=4}} These are listed from north to south;<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Stephen |title=Memories of the Yorkshire fishing industry |url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/10056751.memories-yorkshire-fishing-industry/ |work=York Press |date=19 November 2012}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Name\n!Extant\n!Fishery type\n!Approx no. boats\n!Fish landed\n!Period\n!Notes\n!Ref\n|-\n|[[South Gare]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Ten\n|Codling, plaice, sole turbot, eels\n|Seasonal\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=17}}\n|-\n|[[Coatham]]\n|No\n|Small-scale\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Redcar]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Eleven (five full-time)\n|Cod, whiting, plaice, sole, turbot, crab, lobster\n|Year round\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=17}}\n|-\n|[[Marske-by-the-Sea|Marske]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Three (one full-time)\n|Crab and lobster\n|Year round\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=17}}\n|-\n|[[Saltburn]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|One\n|Cod, flatfish, lobster, crab\n|Year round\n|\n|<ref>{{cite web |title=Saltburn Conservation Area Management Plan |url=https://www.redcar-cleveland.gov.uk/resident/planning-and-building/strategic%20planning/SPD/Documents/Saltburn%20Conservation%20Area%20Management%20Plan%202019.pdf |website=redcar-cleveland.gov.uk |accessdate=7 January 2020 |page=25 |format=PDF |date=October 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Skinningrove]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Four\n|Whitefish, lobster, salmon, sea trout\n|Year round\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=17}}\n|-\n|[[Staithes]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Four\n|Cod, sole, plaice, codling, lobster, crab\n|Year round\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=18}}\n|-\n|[[Port Mulgrave, North Yorkshire|Port Mulgrave]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Two\n|Crab, lobster\n|Summer only\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=18}}\n|-\n|[[Runswick Bay]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Two\n|Flatfish and shellfish\n|Year round\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=18}}\n|-\n|[[Sandsend]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Two\n|Crab, lobster\n|Spring to Autumn\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=18}}\n|-\n|'''[[Whitby]]'''\n|Yes\n|Commercial\n|Twenty\n|cod, haddock, whiting, plaice, lemon sole, sole, rays, dogfish, nephrops, red mullet, saithe, sea bass, pollack, conger eel, brown crab, velvet crab, lobster, salmon, sea trout, mussel, squid\n|Year round\n|Whitby also has visiting boats from outside the Yorkshire Area\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=18}}\n|-\n|[[Robin Hood's Bay]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Five\n|Cod, crab, lobster\n|Seasonal\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=18}}\n|-\n|'''[[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]]'''\n|Yes\n|Commercial\n|Twenty-nine\n|Cod, haddock, whiting, lemon sole, plaice, ray, Dover sole, codling, queen scallop, crab, lobster\n|Year round\n|Scottish vessels catching shellfish also land their catch in Scarborough\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=18\u201319}}\n|-\n|[[Filey]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Five\n|Cod, lobster, sea trout, sole\n|Year round\n|Fish are generally landed from autumn to spring, with lobster fished during the summer\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19}}\n|-\n|[[Flamborough]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Six\n|Cod, ling, pollack, sea bass, lobster\n|Year round\n|As at Filey, the catch changes with the time of year with three boats at the North landing and three at the South landing\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19}}\n|-\n|'''[[Bridlington]]'''\n|Yes\n|Commercial\n|Thirty-eight\n|Shellfish, cod, sole, sea bass, plaice, turbot, sea trout, salmon\n|Year round\n|No boats are based in Bridlington, but nearly 40 boats land their catch there\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19}}\n|-\n|[[Barmston, East Riding of Yorkshire|Barmston]]\n|No\n|Small-scale\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Hornsea]]\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|Eight\n|Sole, cod, whiting, crab, lobster\n|Year round\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19}}\n|-\n|[[Aldbrough, East Riding of Yorkshire|Aldborough]]\n|No\n|Small-scale\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Tunstall, East Riding of Yorkshire|Tunstall]] and [[Withernsea]]\n|Yes\n|Small scale\n|Fifteen\n|Crab, lobster, cod\n|Year round\n|Boats also fish in Withernsea, and the two ports are interchangeable\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19}}\n|-\n|[[Patrington]]\n|No\n|Small-scale\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Easington, East Riding of Yorkshire|Easington]]\n|No\n|Small-scale\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Kilnsea]], [[Spurn Point]] and Stone Creek\n|Yes\n|Small-scale\n|One (some seasonal)\n|Cod, flatfish, crab, lobster\n|Year round\n|\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19}}\n|-\n|[[Paull]]\n|No\n|Small-scale\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|'''[[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]]'''\n|Yes\n|Commercial\n|Eleven\n|Cod, haddock, crab, brown shrimp, dab, sole, plaice, flounder, eel\n|Year round\n|Whitefish is still an important industry in Hull, with most catch being landed at the port already frozen\n|{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19\u201320}}\n|}\n\nThose shown in bold, still land fish commercially in the 21st century.\n\n==Detailed history of ports==\n*''Coatham''\nThe name Coatham derives from cot-ham, a sheltered homestead.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Ekwall |first1=Eilert |title=The concise Oxford dictionary of English place-names |date=1960 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=Oxford |isbn=0-19-869103-3 |page=124 |edition=4}}</ref> It is believed that boats could rest up at Coatham when the weather was bad. Some fishing activity was engaged in here and it was a market town since 1257 compared to the tiny fishing village of Redcar. Both Redcar and Coatham are a contiguous urban area now.<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Redcar |url=https://www.thisisredcar.co.uk/history |website=thisisredcar.co.uk |accessdate=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n*''Redcar''\nThe fishing industry at Redcar started in the early 14th century. Fishing has been mostly crab and lobster, though during the 20th century, the numbers of boats has been in decline.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Forsyth |first1=Ian |title=Redcar's inshore fishing fleet \u2013 in pictures |url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/gallery/2016/feb/12/redcars-inshore-fishing-fleet-in-pictures |accessdate=29 September 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=12 February 2016}}</ref> Line fishing for cod was also undertaken sporadically, but the fishery was largely an inshore concern and the local fishermen say that the cod gave gone further north for colder waters.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seaside town of Redcar boasts Yorkshire\u2019s most unsung piece of history |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/seaside-town-of-redcar-boasts-yorkshire-s-most-unsung-piece-of-history-1-9300149/ |accessdate=29 September 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=15 August 2018}}</ref>\n\n*''Saltburn''\nSaltburn was always a low-key fishing endeavour as it was largely a new town created in the 19th century in an effort led by [[Henry Pease (MP)|Henry Pease]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dowle |first1=Jayne |title=Bargain boltholes in Saltburn by the Sea |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/bargain-boltholes-in-saltburn-by-the-sea-mwpb67zzr99 |accessdate=16 February 2020 |work=The TImes |date=8 June 2007 |language=en|url-access=limited}}</ref> The settlement came under the Parish of Marske and was developed as a new resort in the 1860s, therefore it does not have the same centuries-old fishing histories such as Redcar, Whitby or Robin Hood's Bay.<ref>{{cite web |title=Genuki: Marske By The Sea, Yorkshire (North Riding) |url=https://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/YKS/NRY/MarskeByTheSea |website=www.genuki.org.uk |accessdate=16 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> It still has a small-scale fishing operation.\n\n*''Skinningrove''\n[[File:Yorkshire Cobbles - geograph.org.uk - 602476.jpg|thumb|Yorkshire Cobbles at Skinningrove]]\nSkiningrove had been an important fishing centre since [[Medieval]] times. The arrival of the ironstone industry in the village, and along the Cleveland coast, led to many fishermen abandoning their boats for work in the mines.<ref>{{cite book |title=Skinningrove village trail |publisher=Guisborough Educational Development Centre |location=Guisborough |page=1|oclc=654902228}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Jonathan |title=Classic undulations by the coast |work=Darlington & Stockton Times |issue=34-2019 |date=23 August 2019 |page=59|issn=2516-5348}}</ref>\n\n*''Staithes''\nThe fishermen who worked out of Staithes used line fishing and would not fish on Sundays for religious reasons. In the 1860s  when large trawler fleets from Scarborough, Hull and France threatened fish stocks, many fishermen took jobs in the steel and mining industries. By the end of the 19th century, almost of the population of the village relied on the fishing industry. At least forty-two cobles and fourteen smacks were listed as fishing from Staithes in the 1890s.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Shaw |editor1-first=Michael |title=Frank Meadow Sutcliffe, Hon. F.R.P.S. : Whitby and its people as seen by one of the founders of the naturalistic movement in photography : a third selection of his work |date=1990 |publisher=Sutcliffe Gallery |location=Whitby |isbn=0-9503175-6-X |page=42}}</ref> By the 1950s, only three boats were working out of Staithes. Government incentives persuaded people to go out fishing again, and by 1972, Staithes was listed as being the tenth highest port for the tonnage of lobster it was landing.{{sfn|Wilson|2013|pp=14\u201316}}\n\n*''Port Mulgrave''\nThe port here was not built until 1857 and was initially used to export ironstone from the hills nearby to smelters on the River Tyne. It still supports a small number of fishing cobles who fish for lobster and crab mostly. Part of the dynamiting of the coast to the north was undertaken to allow ships to sail right up to the cliff edge to load ironstone. This has created tanks with seawater in that were used by fishermen to store live lobsters.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trawling for fresh business |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/trawling-for-fresh-business-1-2357295 |accessdate=22 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Hub |date=30 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Walker |first1=Peter |title=Tiny Mulgrave is not any old port in a storm |url=https://www.gazetteherald.co.uk/features/columnists/10206758.tiny-mulgrave-is-not-any-old-port-in-a-storm/ |accessdate=22 August 2019 |work=Gazette & Herald |date=6 February 2013}}</ref> The fishing is seasonal and typically has less than six boats working from the harbour.{{sfn|Gray|1995|p=25}}\n\n*''Runswick Bay''\nRunswick Bay was a \"traditional, ancient fishing village\", though the village is now known as a tourist destination and a location for collecting fossils. Some sea-fishing takes place from here, but in smaller numbers than back in the 18th and 19th centuries,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Swift |first1=Nina |title=\u00a31.5m plan to protect homes in North Yorkshire fishing village threatened by landslips |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/environment/1-5m-plan-to-protect-homes-in-north-yorkshire-fishing-village-threatened-by-landslips-1-9078470 |accessdate=14 October 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=22 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Scarborough Maritime Heritage Centre {{!}} Runswick Bay superstitions - caves and a landslip |url=http://www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk/article.php?article=257 |website=www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Runswick Bay {{!}} Marine Conservation Society |url=https://www.mcsuk.org/beach/runswick-bay |website=www.mcsuk.org |accessdate=14 October 2019}}</ref> when the village had around 20 cables sailing from the harbour.<ref>{{cite news |title=Runswick Bay comes into its own after summer visitors leave |url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/9227799.runswick-bay-comes-summer-visitors-leave/ |accessdate=14 October 2019 |work=York Press |date=1 September 2011}}</ref>\n\n*''Whitby''\nAccounts of Whitby maintained by the monks at [[Whitby Abbey]] show that the port was trading in fish as far back as 1394.{{sfn|Tindale|1987|p=9}}<ref>{{cite book |last1=Barker |first1=Rosalin |editor1-last=Butlin |editor1-first=Robin |title=Historical atlas of North Yorkshire |date=2003 |publisher=Westbury |location=Otley |isbn=1-84103-023-6 |page=211}}</ref> However, in the 12th century, the Abbott in charge at Whitby Abbey was in a dispute with the prior of Bridlington regarding the tithes being applied to the fishermen along the coast.{{sfn|Hall|2013|p=10}}\n\nWhilst strictly not fishing for food, the significance of the port of Whitby as a whaling centre cannot be ignored. Oil and fat from whales had many uses before synthetic and natural substances came available.{{sfn|Tindale|1987|p=20}} However, whale oil and fat were usually imported into Britain from countries that the British were quite often engaged in open warfare with at that time, such as France and Spain.<ref>{{cite web |title=Scarborough Maritime Heritage Centre {{!}} History of the Whitby whaling industry |url=http://www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk/article.php?article=343 |website=www.scarboroughsmaritimeheritage.org.uk |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nGiven the long time dedicated to food fishing, the whaling industry had a short time span. The first ships left Whitby in 1752,{{sfn|Hall|2013|p=12}} whereas the last whaling ship set sail from Whitby for Greenland (where the whaling seas were to be found) in 1837.<ref>{{cite news |title=Nostalgia: Fearless Whitby whalers |url=https://www.thescarboroughnews.co.uk/lifestyle/nostalgia-fearless-whitby-whalers-1-9087764/amp |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=The Scarborough News |date=3 April 2018}}</ref> During this time, Whitby is said to have dispatched over 25,000 seals and 2,761 whales.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hirst |first1=Christopher |title=On the waterfront: Frank Meadow Sutcliffe's Whitby |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/travel/uk/on-the-waterfront-frank-meadow-sutcliffes-whitby-6297902.html? |accessdate=13 August 2019 |work=The Independent |date=4 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nWhitby is now one of two ports along the Yorkshire coast to have a seafood processing plant.<ref>{{cite news |title=Stable raw material prices help boost profit at Whitby Seafoods |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/stable-raw-material-prices-help-boost-profit-at-whitby-seafoods-1-6790420 |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=18 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the catch landed at Whitby totalled {{convert|715|tonne}} with a value of \u00a32.1&nbsp;million,<ref>{{cite news |title=Shellfish catches lead the way for Yorkshire harbours |url=https://fishingnews.co.uk/features/shellfish-catches-lead-the-way-for-yorkshire-harbours/7/ |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=Fishing News |date=29 July 2017}}</ref> but was home to just one trawler, with most fishing being close to shore for crustaceans. In the 1990s, Whitby had 25 trawlers registered to her harbour.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bounds |first1=Andrew |title=Crumbling harbour walls tell Whitby\u2019s tale |url=https://www.ft.com/content/cb7c3f02-4dcd-11e6-88c5-db83e98a590a |accessdate=18 October 2019 |work=Financial Times |date=21 July 2016|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n[[File:Robin Hoods Bay Whitby North Yorkshire Fishing Beach.jpg|thumb|Robin Hoods Bay Whitby North Yorkshire Fishing Beach]]\n\nA third type of fishing at Whitby occurred slightly inland, but involved the catching of sea going fish. Traps were set along the [[River Esk, North Yorkshire|River Esk]], even as far upstream as Ruswarp, so that salmon and sea tout could be caught. This practice is recorded as far back as 1200.{{sfn|Tindale|1987|p=68}}\n\n*''Robin Hood's Bay''\nIn 1530, Robin Hood's Bay was referred to as a \"Fisher townlet of twenty boats\".{{sfn|Hall|2013|p=10}} At that time, it was known to be an important fishing location,<ref>{{cite web |title=History of Robin Hoods Bay, in Scarborough and North Riding {{!}} Map and description |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/place/21607 |website=www.visionofbritain.org.uk |accessdate=16 August 2019}}</ref> with some attaching a greater importance to Robin Hood's Bay than Whitby during the 16th century. Records show that the catch landed at Robin Hood's Bay during these times was larger than at Whitby or Scarborough.{{sfn|Freethy|2012|p=24}} Smuggling overtook fishing as the main industry in the village by the 18th century; this has been attributed to its relative isolation as it was surrounded on three sides by marshy moorland.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lloyd |first1=Chris |title=Looking Back |work=Darlington & Stockton Times |issue=39-2019 |date=27 September 2019 |page=54|issn=2516-5348}}</ref> Even so, in 1816, Whitby had nine fishermen and three fishmongers, Scarborough had three large fishing boats, whereas Robin Hoods Bay had 35 cables and over 130 fishermen.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dalton |first1=William |title=Guide to Robin Hood's Bay and District |date=1909 |publisher=Dalton |location=Robin Hood's Bay |page=17|oclc=558760365}}</ref>\n\n*''Scarborough''\nIn 1252, an edict passed by Henry III dictated the levies taxed against boats entering Scarborough Harbour. Thus was between four and sixpence for fishermen depending on the size of the boat.{{sfn|Coggins|1991|p=97}} Fish land at Scarborough included cod, halibut, ling, turbot, skate, lobster, crab, shrimp, mackerel, sole, dab, plaice, herring, gurnard  Whiting, coalfish and haddock.{{sfn|Coggins|1991|p=105}} But by far the greatest importance was placed upon the herring. It was such a great part of the fishing economy despite the season only lasting for August and September.{{sfn|Coggins|1991|p=108}} However, the landings were good; in the 1870s, this amounted to such a large tonnage that an express fish train to London left Scarborough daily.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Fawcett |first1=Bill |title=A history of the York-Scarborough Railway. |date=1995 |publisher=Hutton Press |location=Cherry Burton |isbn=1-872167-71-3 |page=61}}</ref>\n\n*''Filey''\nExports from Filey were historically greater than that of Hull; it was only down to the latter's railway and dock expansion that its exports overtook those of Filey. Of particular importance were skate wings and other dried fish which were in demand in Portugal especially, but also in France.{{sfn|Freethy|2012|p=43}}\n\nAs in most fishing villages, the women folk of Filey were involved in the fishing industry. Known as ''Flither Girls'', women would scour the coastline looking for limpets which the fishermen would use as bait for catching fish such as herring. Flither is a local term for limpet.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Freeman |first1=Sarah |title=Tales of the limpet girls who stuck to their task |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/tales-of-the-limpet-girls-who-stuck-to-their-task-1-2481655/ |accessdate=19 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=7 September 2005}}</ref>{{sfn|Freethy|2012|p=45}} In the 1960s, eleven boats were working out of the shoreline to fish for crab and lobster.{{sfn|Edwards|1967|p=4}} Filey has suffered a downtown in the 21st century, with many boats leaving for Scarborough to work from.<ref>{{cite news |title=FISH INDUSTRY ON THE VERGE OF COLLAPSE |url=https://www.fileymercury.co.uk/news/business/fish-industry-on-the-verge-of-collapse-1-3318697 |accessdate=1 January 2020 |work=The Filey Mercury |date=23 April 2011 |language=en}}</ref> The fishermen at Filey now fish only between April and August and whilst sea trout is an accepted catch, salmon must not be caught or landed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Warner |first1=Mike |title=Why Filey\u2019s fishermen fear they may be the last generation to cast their nets |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/analysis/why-filey-s-fishermen-fear-they-may-be-the-last-generation-to-cast-their-nets-1-9043304 |accessdate=1 January 2020 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=3 March 2018 |language=en|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\n*''Flamborough''\n[[File:Cobles at north landing.JPG|thumb|Cobles at North Landing, Flamborough. The old [[Flamborough Lifeboat Station|Flamborough North]] lifeboat station is in the background.]]\nFishing out of North Landing at Flamborough can be traced as far back as the 13th century, and like many other locations on the east coast, it utilised cobles.<ref>{{cite web |title=Flamborough Head |url=http://www.flamboroughheadsac.org.uk/storyboards/fishing/ |website=www.flamboroughheadsac.org.uk |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> In the 1960s, ten boats were based out of Flamborough primarily engaged in fishing for crab and lobster.{{sfn|Edwards|1967|p=4}} In the 21st century, this had been reduced to six boats.{{sfn|Walmsley|Pawson|2007|p=19}}\n\n*''Bridlington''\n[[File:Holderness coast fishing stats in 2010.svg|thumb|Holderness coast fishing stats in 2010]]\nFishing from Bridlington goes back centuries, although official records detailing registered vessels only extend as far back as 1786.<ref name=\"BFP\">{{cite news |title=Archive cobles together boating heritage pictures |url=https://www.bridlingtonfreepress.co.uk/news/archive-cobles-together-boating-heritage-pictures-1-8064090 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |work=Bridlington Free Press |date=11 August 2016 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nBridlington is now the leading shellfish port in Europe, landing over {{convert|420|tonne}} in 2014, which had risen to {{convert|539|tonne}}, with a value of \u00a31.6&nbsp;million by 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=Provisional Results Monthly UK Sea Fisheries Statistics - Reported Landings: December 2018 |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/779478/Monthly_UK_Sea_Fisheries_Statistics_-_December_2018.pdf |website=assets.publishing.service.gov.uk |accessdate=1 January 2020 |pages=1\u20132 |format=PDF |date=February 2019}}</ref> Most of the lobsters and other shellfish landed at Bridlington are exported, mainly to France, Spain and Portugal.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Grainger |first1=John |title=Why Bridlington is the lobster capital of Europe |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/why-bridlington-is-the-lobster-capital-of-europe-1-8122806 |accessdate=3 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=13 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=East Yorkshire Coast - The Holderness Coast Fishery |url=http://www.eastyorkshirecoast.com/14-content/the-coast-at-work/51-the-holderness-coast-fishery.html |website=www.eastyorkshirecoast.com |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref> In 2017, work started on a lobster hatchery in the port of Bridlington for the purposes of research into the species.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bridlington (Lobster Hatchery and Research Facility) 2019 {{!}} West of Morecambe Fisheries |url=https://www.westofmorecambe.com/community-projects/lobster-hatchery-and-research-facility/ |website=westofmorecambe.com |accessdate=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, the Holderness shellfish industry was estimated to have 145 people employed across 66 boats. The value of the shellfish catch across Holderness was \u00a36&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shellfishermen net \u00a31m boost to help develop top UK fishery |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/shellfishermen-net-1m-boost-to-help-develop-top-uk-fishery-1-4010134 |accessdate=31 January 2020 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=28 November 2011 |language=en}}</ref>\n\n*''Hornsea''\nFishing in Hornsea was largely concentrated on the Mere form as early as the 13th century.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Robinson |first1=Robb |title=East Yorkshire Coast - A History of Fishing in East Yorkshire |url=http://www.eastyorkshirecoast.com/articles/the-coast-at-work/14-content/the-coast-at-work/21-a-history-of-fishing-in-east-yorkshire.html |website=www.eastyorkshirecoast.com |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> However, a seaborne trade in fishing (and other goods) flourished from the 16th century onwards, with cobles being launched from the beck that drained the mere into the sea.<ref>{{cite web |title=North division: Hornsea {{!}} British History Online |url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/yorks/east/vol7/pp273-295 |website=www.british-history.ac.uk |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> In 2009, the fishery landed over {{convert|320|tonne}} of mailnt shellfish.{{sfn|HCF|2011|p=13}}\n\n*''Withernsea''\nLike Saltburn, Withernsea does not have a long-standing history of fishing. The landing of fish in the town was hoped to be increased when the railway arrived in Withernsea, however, the location of the town was so near to the Port of Hull, that most boats could land their catch there instead.<ref>{{cite web |title=East Yorkshire Coast - The Fishing Heritage of Withernsea |url=http://www.eastyorkshirecoast.com/15-content/explore-the-shore/108-the-fishing-heritage-of-withernsea.html |website=www.eastyorkshirecoast.com |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref> Fishing is still continued on a small basis, which land shellfish and flatfish, with a small sideline in intertidal netting for sea-trout.{{sfn|HCF|2011|p=15}}\n*''Humber fisheries''\nThe lost village of [[Ravenser Odd]] was noted for its herring industry as far back as 1360. Herring landed at Ravneser Odd was traded throughout Europe and attracted many fish merchants from across England to its sales.{{sfn|HCF|2011|pp=11\u201312}}\n\nDuring the 18th and 19th centuries, fishermen working out of Patrington and Paull, fished the Humber Estuary for prawns and shrimp which were then sold in the local area.<ref>{{cite web |title=East Yorkshire Coast - A History of Fishing in East Yorkshire |url=http://www.eastyorkshirecoast.com/14-content/the-coast-at-work/21-a-history-of-fishing-in-east-yorkshire.html |website=www.eastyorkshirecoast.com |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref> Shrimp fishing was still taking place in the Humber Estuary well into the 1990s when special trawls were undertaken in the autumn months.{{sfn|Uglow|1991|p=184}}\n\n*''Kingston upon Hull''\nHull was recognised as one of the great fishing towns of the world and what one writer described as being the \"vanguard of innovative developments in the industry for much of this [the 20th] century\".{{sfn|Uglow|1991|p=180}} Before the [[Cod Wars]], Hull was the third largest port in Britain for fish landings.<ref>{{cite news |last1=English |first1=Charlie |title=To Hull and back: the rebirth of Britain\u2019s poorest city |url=https://www.theguardian.com/cities/2014/sep/11/-sp-to-hull-and-back-the-rebirth-of-britains-poorest-city |accessdate=12 January 2020 |work=The Guardian |date=11 September 2014}}</ref> A much reduced trawler fleet still calls Hull home, but as the vessels they operate are up to {{convert|70|m|order=flip}} in length and are true trawlers, they tend to fish in deeper waters away from the Yorkshire Coast (in the seas off the Faroe Islands, Greenland, Iceland and Norway).<ref>{{cite web |title=Summary of commercial marine fishing by English and Welsh vessels \u2265 10 metres LOA for 2004 |url=http://www.cefas.co.uk/Publications/techrep/tech134.pdf |website=cefas.co.uk |accessdate=1 January 2020 |page=16 |format=PDF |date=2006}}</ref>\n\n==Shipbuilding==\n[[File:Parkol Marine shipyard Whitby.jpg|thumb|[[Parkol Marine Engineering|Parkol Marine]] shipyard, Whitby]]\nBesides fishing, a secondary business involved shipbuilding, some of the most notable were;\n*[[Cook, Welton & Gemmell]] \u2013 who had a shipbuilding yard on the River Hull at Beverley,<ref>{{cite news |title=New film shows town's shipbuilding heritage |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-49370482 |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=BBC News |date=16 August 2019}}</ref> and another on the estuary at Hull where [[The Deep]] now stands. they traded from 1883 to 1963 at Beverley, though the demand for heavier ships could not be accommodated at Beverley which was {{convert|9|mi}} upstream on the [[River Hull]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New film shows town's shipbuilding heritage |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-49370482 |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=16 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Exhibition keeps river shipyard's fame afloat |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/exhibition-keeps-river-shipyard-s-fame-afloat-1-2541490 |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=15 March 2004}}</ref>\n*[[Cochrane Shipbuilders]] \u2013 founded in [[Selby]] in 1884, the yard became Cohrane's & Sons, before changing hands many times during the second half of the twentieth century. The yard was closed in 1992 and all the equipment was auctioned off in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lewis |first1=Stephen |title=Great days of the Selby shipyard remembered |url=https://www.yorkpress.co.uk/news/14739983.great-days-of-the-selby-shipyard-remembered/ |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=York Press |date=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n*Tony Goodall \u2013 Goodall worked at Sandsend between 1953 and 1995 where he built cobles for the local fishing industry.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Greenhill |first1=Basil |title=Inshore craft : traditional working vessels of the British Isles |date=1997 |publisher=Seaforth |location=Barnsley |isbn=978-1-84832-167-0 |page=118}}</ref>\n*Goole Shipbuilding and Repairing Company \u2013 built mostly larger ocean going transport vessels or ships for the Royal Navy. Also built some of the larger trawlers for use in UK waters.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Site for information on Keels and Sloops in the Humber Area |url=http://www.humberpacketboats.co.uk/goole.html |website=www.humberpacketboats.co.uk |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Parkol Marine Engineering]] \u2013 one of a small number of extant shipbuilders in Britain who build fishing boats. The company are based in Whitby,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jones |first1=Sam |title=Parkol-built fishing trawler sets sail, as company says demand for vessels is doubling |url=https://www.whitbygazette.co.uk/news/parkol-built-fishing-trawler-sets-sail-as-company-says-demand-for-vessels-is-doubling-1-9198806/ |accessdate=16 August 2019 |work=Whitby Gazette |date=8 June 2018}}</ref> with another build plant on Teesside.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mayor visits Parkol Marine Engineering after Tees Valley move |url=https://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/business/16891205.mayor-visits-shipbuilder-parkol-marine-engineering-after-tees-valley-move/ |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=The Northern Echo |date=20 September 2018}}</ref>\n*Pickersgill & Sons - based in Thornaby-on-Tees, the firm ceased boatbuilding in the 1960s.{{sfn|Wilson|2013|p=117}}\n\nMany more detailed descriptions are contained in the [[Ship and boat building in Whitby]] article.\n\n==Registration of boats==\n[[File:Small fishing boats in Whitby harbour - geograph.org.uk - 914353.jpg|thumb|Small fishing boats in Whitby harbour. The boat on the right is ''WY150'', a boat with a Whitby code.]]\n[[File:FlamboroughNorthLandingBoats.JPG|thumb|Flamborough North Landing Boats. Both boats are registered to Hull; H453 is called ''Prosperity'', and H358 is called ''Summer Rose''. Both work out of Flamborough catching shellfish.<ref name=\"MMO1\"/>]]\nBoats are given registration letters for the port they are allocated to. In Yorkshire, the codes are;\n*GE = Goole\n*H = (Kingston upon) Hull\n*MH = Middlesbrough\n*SH = Scarbrough\n*WY = Whitby.<ref>{{cite web |title=Fishing boat registration codes |url=https://www.padstow-harbour.co.uk/fishing_boat_reg_codes.pdf |website=padstow-harbour.co.uk |accessdate=16 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany of the boats registered to Hornsea and Withernsea have a GY code, which is for Grimsby. Some boats which are registered to one of the Yorkshire home ports, may have codes for outside the Yorkshire region, such as Stornoway or Fowey. A sample of the number of boats and their registrations for 1967 and 2020 is given below.  In 2020, vessels are registered as being either under, or over {{convert|10|m}}, with the Marine Management Organisation (MMO).<ref name=\"MMO1\">{{cite web |title=Vessel lists 10 metres and under |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/vessel-lists-10-metres-and-under |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=16 February 2020 |language=en |format=.xls}}</ref><ref name=\"MMO2\">{{cite web |title=Vessel lists over 10 metres |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/vessel-lists-over-10-metres |website=GOV.UK |accessdate=16 February 2020 |language=en |format=.xls}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Boats registered in Yorkshire based on size.<ref name=\"MMO1\"/><ref name=\"MMO2\"/>{{sfn|Edwards|1967|p=5}}\n!Port\n!> 40&nbsp;ft boats 1967\n!< 40&nbsp;ft boats 1967\n!> 33&nbsp;ft boats 2020\n!< 33&nbsp;ft boats 2020\n!Notes\n|-\n|Redcar\n|3\n|0\n|27\n|0\n|All 2020 boats are registered in North Shields (SN), but most have a Middlesbrough (MH) code\n|-\n|Staithes\n|5\n|0\n|4\n|0\n|All boats are registered in Scarborough, though some have been registered in Hartlepool (HL){{sfn|Wilson|2013|p=21}}\n|-\n|Whitby\n|14\n|13\n|28\n|9\n|Whilst Whitby has its own code (WY), all boats are registered in Scarborough\n|-\n|Scarborough\n|25\n|2\n|24\n|11\n|One boat is registered to Fleetwood\n|-\n|Filey\n|11\n|0\n|1\n|0\n|All boats are registered in Scarborough\n|-\n|Flamborough\n|10\n|0\n|4\n|0\n|All boats are registered in Scarborough\n|-\n|Bridlington\n|7\n|8\n|17\n|23\n|All boats are registered in Scarborough bar one, which is registered in Campbelltown\n|-\n|Hornsea\n|\u2666\n|\u2666\n|19\n|0\n|All boats are registered in Grimsby\n|-\n|Withernsea\n|\u2666\n|\u2666\n|12\n|0\n|All boats are registered in Grimsby\n|-\n|Hull\n|\u2666\n|\u2666\n|0\n|10\n|Whilst Hull has its own registration (H), all boats are registered in Grimsby\n|}\n\n\u2666 Means that data is not available\n\n==Culture==\nThe feature film ''[[Turn of the Tide]]'' was filmed in and around Whitby and Robin Hood's Bay.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Shafer |first1=Stephen C |title=British popular films, 1929-1939 : the cinema of reassurance |date=1997 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=0-415-00282-6 |page=191}}</ref> The story revolves around the rivalry between two fishing families and features the Bay Hotel in Robin Hood's Bay.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wragg |first1=Amanda |title=Pub of the Week: The Bay Hotel, Robin Hood\u2019s Bay |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/best-in-yorkshire/restaurants/pub-of-the-week-the-bay-hotel-robin-hood-s-bay-1-8152567 |accessdate=17 February 2020 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=1 October 2016 |language=en|url-access=limited}}</ref> Disappointed by the take up for his first film, [[J Arthur Rank]] started his own distribution company to market the film properly.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Waites |editor1-first=Bernard |editor2-last=Bennett |editor2-first=Tony |editor3-last=Martin |editor3-first=Graham |title=Popular culture, past and present : a reader |date=1982 |publisher=Routledge |location=London |isbn=978-0-415-04033-4 |page=152}}</ref>\n\nBridlington holds a sea food festival sporadically (2011, 2016, 2019), to emphasise the importance of being the largest shellfish port in Europe.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edwards |first1=John |title=Bridlington Seafood Festival is coming back this summer |url=https://www.bridlingtonfreepress.co.uk/whats-on/bridlington-seafood-festival-is-coming-back-this-summer-1-9651930/ |accessdate=18 August 2019 |work=Bridlington Free Press |date=15 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nFiley is host to the ''Filey Fishermen's Choir'' who trace their origins back to \n1823.<ref>{{cite news |title=Video: Filey Fishermen\u2019s Choir - Battle to keep the traditions of the seaside alive |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/lifestyle/travel/video-filey-fishermen-s-choir-battle-to-keep-the-traditions-of-the-seaside-alive-1-8004834/ |accessdate=18 August 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=8 June 2016|url-access=limited}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019, Whitby held its first Fish & Ships festival which celebrated the stories and history of fishing at sea.<ref>{{cite news |title=Experience the seafarers\u2019 way of life from sea to shore at new festival |url=https://www.whitbygazette.co.uk/news/experience-the-seafarers-way-of-life-from-sea-to-shore-at-new-festival-1-9757548 |accessdate=27 July 2019 |work=The Whitby Gazette |date=9 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Museums and historical==\nStarting in 1989, every January or February, there is a ''Lost Trawlermen's Memorial Day'' held at [[St Andrew's Dock]] in Hull. The service remembers the 6,000 men who died at sea whilst engaged in fishing. The number of dead only accounts for those lost at sea who sailed from Hull and the time of year is intended as that was hen most ships were lost.<ref>{{cite news |title=Service held for trawlermen lost at sea |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-humber-46939785 |accessdate=15 October 2019 |work=BBC News |date=20 January 2019}}</ref>\n*The [[Arctic Corsair]] \u2013 a floating museum on the River Hull in Kingston upon Hull. The Arctic Corsair was traditionally a side winder trawler that was active during the Cod Wars.<ref>{{cite web |title=Name Arctic Corsair {{!}} National Historic Ships |url=https://www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk/register/628/arctic-corsair |website=www.nationalhistoricships.org.uk |accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref>\n*Bridlington Maritime Trail - a walk around the harbour and south side of Bridlington<ref>{{cite news |title=Bridlington Maritime Trail |url=https://www.bridlingtonfreepress.co.uk/lifestyle/bridlington-maritime-trail-1-1709632/ |accessdate=15 August 2019 |work=Bridlington Free Press |date=7 November 2006}}</ref>\n*Hull Fish Trail \u2013 a walk around Hull with 41 sculptures of life sized fish.<ref>{{cite web |first2= |title=Hull Fish Trail {{!}} Town Trail {{!}} Hull{{!}}East Yorkshire |url=https://www.visithullandeastyorkshire.com/Hull-Hull-Fish-Trail/details/?dms=3&venue=2298110 |website=www.visithullandeastyorkshire.com |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n*The [[Viola (trawler)|Viola]] \u2013 a trawler built in Beverley and used in the North Sea fishing fleet from Hull until requisitioned by the [[Royal Navy]] in the [[First World War]]. She is in a derelict condition at [[Grytviken]] on [[South Georgia Island|South Georgia]], although efforts continue to return the vessel to Hull as a permanent showpiece.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Copping |first1=Jasper |title=Viola: the trawler that fought World War One |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/history/world-war-one/10220437/Viola-the-trawler-that-fought-World-War-One.html |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=3 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Hannah |title=Calls to bring back historic trawler for Hull's \u00a327m project |url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/whats-on/whats-on-news/calls-bring-back-historic-trawler-2694445 |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=Hull Daily Mail |date=28 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n[[File:Chapel Street and the Fishermans Memorial - geograph.org.uk - 1768873.jpg|thumb|Chapel Street and the Fishermans Memorial in Flamborough]]\n*5 February 1909 \u2013 A fleet of 40 or 50 cobles were fishing in the bay off the North Landing when a gale \"whipped the sea up into mountainous waves\". The three occupants of one boat, ''Gleaner'', found themselves washed overboard and another boat the ''Two Brothers'', stopped to help the stricken men. The one boat with six men was then upturned by another rogue wave and all six drowned within sight of the shore and beyond the reach of the lifeboat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fishing disaster remembered 100 years on |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/latest-news/fishing-disaster-remembered-100-years-on-1-2333464 |accessdate=16 February 2020 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=2 February 2009 |language=en}}</ref> A memorial was later installed in the village to commemorate the dead.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coble tragedy remembered |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/humber/content/articles/2009/02/09/1909_fishing_disaster.shtml |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=16 February 2020 |language=en-gb}}</ref>\n*9 January 1935 \u2013 The trawler, The Edgar Wallace, was coming into port at St Andrews Dock in Hull, when it hit a sandbank and capsized. Water rushed into the cabins and 15 members of her crew drowned, with the three survivors swept overboard, but being rescued by passing ships.<ref>{{cite web |title=Tragic verse |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/humber/content/articles/2009/07/06/trawler_poem_feature.shtml |website=www.bbc.co.uk |accessdate=27 July 2019 |date=7 July 2009}}</ref>\n*25\u201326 January 1955 \u2013 the trawlers ''Lorella'' and ''Rodrigo'' were in a safe haven off Iceland, sitting out a ferocious storm. Another trawler, the ''Kingston Garnet'', was nearby with her propeller fast on some wire in the sea. Both the ''Lorella'' and the ''Rodrigo'' left what was described as \"[a] comfy place, but they went back into that living hell to try and save those guys.\" Both ships foundered when ocean spray froze instantly on the rigging, normally {{convert|0.5|in}} thick, but swelling to {{convert|7|in}} thick with the frozen water. Both ships rolled over and up until the last minute, they were still radioing what was happening. 40 men lost their lives in the sinking; no bodies were found.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Campbell |first1=James |title=Calls to honour hero crews who died in tragic rescue attempt |url=https://www.hulldailymail.co.uk/news/history/honour-heroes-tragic-rescue-attempt-1134717 |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=Hull Daily Mail |date=30 January 2018}}</ref> Both ships were lost {{convert|90|nmi}} off of Icelands' North East Cape.<ref>{{cite web |title=WRECKSITE - RODERIGO TRAWLER 1950-1955 |url=https://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?167032 |website=www.wrecksite.eu |accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=WRECKSITE - LORELLA TRAWLER 1947-1955 |url=https://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?156485 |website=www.wrecksite.eu |accessdate=17 October 2019}}</ref>\n*[[Arctic Viking|Arctic Viking (1961)]]\n*[[Hull triple trawler tragedy (1968)]]\n*[[FV Gaul|FV Gaul (1974)]]\n* October 1976 \u2013 The trawler ''Admiral Von Tromp'' set out from the port of Scarborough with her destination being the Barnacle Banks some {{convert|45|nmi}} north east of Scarborough. Somehow she ended up stranded on Saltwick Nab some 90 degrees off course. the man at the wheel and one other deckhand drowned that night, the others were rescued by the Whitby Lifeboat or washed ashore. At the inquest into the sinking, a nautical expert claimed that even if the ship had been left to her own devices, she would not have foundered on Saltwick Nab. The inquest concluded that the wheelman had piloted the vessel onto the rocks deliberately.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Newton |first1=Grace |title=Nobody knows why this shipwreck on the Yorkshire coast ran aground |url=https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/nobody-knows-why-this-shipwreck-on-the-yorkshire-coast-ran-aground-1-9083951 |accessdate=17 October 2019 |work=The Yorkshire Post |date=1 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Fishing in Cornwall]]\n*[[Big-game tunny fishing off Scarborough]]\n*[[Whitby Seafoods Ltd]]\n*[[Yorkshire Coast]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{cite book|editor-last=Coggins|editor-first=Dennis|title=Scarborough in Old Photographs|year=1991|publisher=Alan Sutton|location=Stroud|isbn=0-86299-932-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite report|last=Edwards|first=Eric|title=Yorkshire Crab Stocks|date=September 1967|publisher=Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Food - Fisheries Laboratory|location=Burnham-on-Crouch|oclc=155719912|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Freethy|first=Ron|title=Memories of the Yorkshire Fishing Industry|date=2012|publisher=Countryside Books|location=Newbury|isbn=978-1-84674-264-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Godfrey|first=Arthur|title=Yorkshire Fishing Fleets; the Story of Yorkshire's Oldest and Most Dangerous Industry|year=1974|publisher=Dalesman Books|location=Clapham|isbn=0-85206-245-1|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite report|last=Gray|first= M G|title=The coastal fisheries of England and Wales, Part III: A review of their status 1992-1994|date=1995|publisher=Directorate of Fisheries Research|location=Lowestoft|issn=0308-5589|ref=harv}}\n*{{ cite report| last=Hall| first=Chris|title=Whitby Conservation Area \u2013 Character Appraisal & Management Plan | date=January 2013|url= https://www.scarborough.gov.uk/home/planning/conservation/conservation-area-appraisals-and-management-plans/whitby-conservation|format=PDF|accessdate=13 August 2019|publisher=Scarborough Borough Council|location=Scarborough |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite report|title=Holderness Coast Fishery Local Action Group Draft Strategy|date=May 2011|url=https://www.eastriding.gov.uk/corp-survey/snapform/Weblinks/FLAGdraftstrategy.pdf|format=PDF|accessdate=20 August 2019|publisher=Holderness Coast FLAG|website=eastriding.gov.uk|ref={{harvid|HCF|2011}} }}\n*{{cite book|last=Hoole|first=Ken|title=Railway Stations of the North East|year=1985|publisher=David & Charles|location=Newton Abbot|isbn=0-7153-8527-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Tindale|first=John|title=Fishing out of Whitby|year=1987|publisher=Dalesman Books|location=Clapham|isbn=0-85206-912-X|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Uglow|first=R F|title=The Yorkshire Coast|chapter=13: Yorkshire Fisheries|editor-last=Lewis|editor-first=David B|year=1991|publisher=Normandy Press|location=Beverley|isbn=0-9507665-3-4|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/yorkshirecoast0000unse}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Walmsley|first1=S A|last2=Pawson|first2=M G|title=The coastal fisheries of England and Wales, Part V: a review of their status 2005\u20136|date=2007|publisher=CEFAS|location=Lowestoft|journal=Science series technical report|issue=140|issn=0308-5589|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wilson|first=Gloria|title=Fishing Boats of Cleveland and North Yorkshire|year=2013|publisher=The History Press|location=Stroud|isbn=978-0-7524-8041-1|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fishing in Yorkshire}}\n*[http://www.yorkshirefilmarchive.com/film/record-project-film-3-decline-hull-fishing-industry The Decline of the Hull Fishing Industry on the Yorkshire Film Archive]\n*[http://www.yorkshirefilmarchive.com/film/beverley-shipyard A profile of Beverley (silent) - shipyard section begins at 06:23]\n*[http://www.ne-ifca.gov.uk/about-us/history/ North Eastern Inshore Fisheries and Conservation Authority]\n*[https://www.britishpathe.com/video/trawler-disaster-at-hull-news-in-a-nutshell British Path\u00e9 news report on the sinking of the Edgar Wallace]\n*[https://www.whitbyonline.co.uk/whitbyhistory/whaling.php Whaling in Whitby]\n*[http://www.yorkshirefilmarchive.com/film/pot-luck Film of the ''Wayside Flower'' fishing for shellfish out of Bridlington in 1962]\n*[http://www.bridlingtonharbour.com/bridlington-sailing-coble-preservation-society/ Bridlington Coble Preservation Society]\n*[https://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/heritage/how-the-tide-turned-for-hull-s-fishing-dock-1-7636913 St Andrews Dock, Hull - fish dock connected to NER later LNER]\n\n{{The Yorkshire coast}}\n{{fishing history}}\n{{fisheries and fishing}}\n\n[[Category:Fishing in England]]\n[[Category:History of fishing]]\n[[Category:Traditional boats]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toDeep(link changed toThe Deep (aquarium)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yorkshire_coast_fishery"}
{"title_page": "C. Laxma Reddy", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n|name               = Dr. C. Laxma Reddy\n|image        = [[File:155A9996.jpg|200px|]]\n|image_size        = \n|caption            =\n|office       = Minister for Health, Medical Education and Family Welfare, [[Government of Telangana]] \n|term_start   = 2014\n|term_end     = 2018\n|succeeding   = \n|predecessor  = [[T. Rajaiah]]\n|successor    = \n| office1 = Member of Legislative Assembly\n|term_start1   = 17 December 2014\n|term_end1     = \n|succeeding1   = \n|predecessor1  =\n| constituency = [[Jadcherla (Assembly constituency)|Jadcherla]]\n|birth_place        = \n|residence          = [[Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]], India\n| spouse = Dr.Sweta\n|alma_mater         = Hyderabad Karnataka Education Society\n|party              = [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]]\n|education = B.H.M.S (Homeopathic Medicine)}}\nDr.''' Charlakola Laxma Reddy''' (born 3 February 1962) is the EX Health Minister of Telangana, serving 2014\u20132018. He is present [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of Legislative Assembly]] for [[Jadcherla (Assembly constituency)|Jadcherla constituency]] representing [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]]. He served as the first Energy Minister for Telangana state and then was moved to take over the Health portfolio. He is also a former homeopathic doctor.\n\n==Early life and education==\nReddy was born in [[Jadcherla]] and hails from Avancha Village of Thimmajipet Mandal. He received his graduation in [[Bachelor of Homoeopathic Medical Sciences]] from Hyderabad Karnataka Education Society, Gulbarga, Karnataka. He was a Student Leader President. Later he practiced as a Homeopathic Doctor at [[Jadcherla]] before entering into politics.<ref>[http://www.telanganastateinfo.com/c-laxma-reddy-profile-wiki/ Profile of Minister]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLaxma Reddy was very active in politics and held many posts from quite a young age. He started his political career as a sarpanch of his village, Avancha, in Thimmajipeta Mandal. Eventually, He did several services to Single Window System and Library Society at Thimmajipeta mandal level.\n\n===TRS Party===\nHe joined [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]] after K. Chandrashekhar Rao launched the party in 2001 and has been a key leader in the state movement. He won from the [[Jadcherla]] Constituency in 2004 Assembly Elections, but with KCR's call, Reddy was the first to resign his position in April 2008 when the Central government did not meet their demand for a separate state, but tragically lost the by-elections.<ref>[http://www.elections.in/telangana/assembly-constituencies/jadcherla.html Jadcherla MLAs]</ref>\n\nHe was widely praised across the TRS party and by KCR as he was the only MLA of TRS party from Mahabubnagar District where the Telangana movement was the weakest in the state at the time.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} He supported KCR while contesting the Mahabubnagar MP seat, though he was not allocated seat in 2009 due to an alliance of TRS.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} Dr. Reddy had played a major role in the victory of KCR as he was only TRS leader in Mahabubnagar. The victory of KCR, accelerated the Telangana agitation where KCR as an Mahabubnagar MP took the fast-unto-death protest. Finally later achieving Telangana. Thereupon, often said that he was the leader who took up the Telangana movement on his shoulders in the southern most region when he was either in power or not.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===As Minister===\nIn 2014 Assembly elections, he was re-elected from Jadcherla and was inducted into Cabinet as Electricity Minister. After sacking of Deputy CM [[T. Rajaiah]] as Health Minister, Reddy replaced him and was handed over the Medical and Health Department.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Rajaiah-gets-marching-orders-Kadiam-made-Telangana-deputy-CM/articleshow/46016029.cms Rajaih gets marching orders]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to Dr. Swetha and has two children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n{{Cabinet of K Chandrashekar Rao}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reddy, C. Laxma}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Telangana Rashtra Samithi politicians]]\n[[Category:State cabinet ministers of Telangana]]\n[[Category:Telugu politicians]]\n[[Category:Telangana politicians]]\n[[Category:Telangana MLAs 2014\u20132018]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{infobox officeholder\n|name               = Dr. C. Laxma Reddy\n|image        = [[File:155A9996.jpg|200px|]]\n|image_size        = \n|caption            =\n|office       = Minister for Health, Medical Education and Family Welfare, [[Government of Telangana]] \n|term_start   = 2014\n|term_end     = 2018\n|succeeding   = \n|predecessor  = [[T. Rajaiah]]\n|successor    = \n| office1 = Member of Legislative Assembly\n|term_start1   = 17 December 2014\n|term_end1     = \n|succeeding1   = \n|predecessor1  =\n| constituency = [[Jadcherla (Assembly constituency)|Jadcherla]]\n|birth_place        = \n|residence          = [[Hyderabad]], [[Telangana]], India\n| spouse = Dr.Sweta\n|alma_mater         = Hyderabad Karnataka Education Society\n|party              = [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]]\n|education = B.H.M.S (Homeopathic Medicine)}}\nDr.''' Charlakola Laxma Reddy''' (born 3 February 1962) is the former Health Minister of Telangana, serving 2014\u20132018. He is present [[Member of Legislative Assembly (India)|Member of Legislative Assembly]] for [[Jadcherla (Assembly constituency)|Jadcherla constituency]] representing [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]]. He served as the first Energy Minister for Telangana state and then was moved to take over the Health portfolio. He is also a former homeopathic doctor.\n\n==Early life and education==\nReddy was born in [[Jadcherla]] and hails from Avancha Village of Thimmajipet Mandal. He received his graduation in [[Bachelor of Homoeopathic Medical Sciences]] from Hyderabad Karnataka Education Society, Gulbarga, Karnataka. He was a Student Leader President. Later he practiced as a Homeopathic Doctor at [[Jadcherla]] before entering into politics.<ref>[http://www.telanganastateinfo.com/c-laxma-reddy-profile-wiki/ Profile of Minister]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nLaxma Reddy was very active in politics and held many posts from quite a young age. He started his political career as a sarpanch of his village, Avancha, in Thimmajipeta Mandal. Eventually, He did several services to Single Window System and Library Society at Thimmajipeta mandal level.\n\n===TRS Party===\nHe joined [[Telangana Rashtra Samithi]] after K. Chandrashekhar Rao launched the party in 2001 and has been a key leader in the state movement. He won from the [[Jadcherla]] Constituency in 2004 Assembly Elections, but with KCR's call, Reddy was the first to resign his position in April 2008 when the Central government did not meet their demand for a separate state, but tragically lost the by-elections.<ref>[http://www.elections.in/telangana/assembly-constituencies/jadcherla.html Jadcherla MLAs]</ref>\n\nHe was widely praised across the TRS party and by KCR as he was the only MLA of TRS party from Mahabubnagar District where the Telangana movement was the weakest in the state at the time.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} He supported KCR while contesting the Mahabubnagar MP seat, though he was not allocated seat in 2009 due to an alliance of TRS.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}} Dr. Reddy had played a major role in the victory of KCR as he was only TRS leader in Mahabubnagar. The victory of KCR, accelerated the Telangana agitation where KCR as an Mahabubnagar MP took the fast-unto-death protest. Finally later achieving Telangana. Thereupon, often said that he was the leader who took up the Telangana movement on his shoulders in the southern most region when he was either in power or not.{{citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\n===As Minister===\nIn 2014 Assembly elections, he was re-elected from Jadcherla and was inducted into Cabinet as Electricity Minister. After sacking of Deputy CM [[T. Rajaiah]] as Health Minister, Reddy replaced him and was handed over the Medical and Health Department.<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/hyderabad/Rajaiah-gets-marching-orders-Kadiam-made-Telangana-deputy-CM/articleshow/46016029.cms Rajaih gets marching orders]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to Dr. Swetha and has two children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n{{Cabinet of K Chandrashekar Rao}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Reddy, C. Laxma}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Telangana Rashtra Samithi politicians]]\n[[Category:State cabinet ministers of Telangana]]\n[[Category:Telugu politicians]]\n[[Category:Telangana politicians]]\n[[Category:Telangana MLAs 2014\u20132018]]\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n", "name_user": "2409:4070:188:cc4a:2c91:f6c7:3f66:6ab9", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._Laxma_Reddy"}
{"title_page": "Bloop", "text_new": "{{short description|Sound detected in 1997 from a non-tectonic cryoseism (ice quake)}}\n{{other uses|Bloop (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Bloop.jpg|250px|thumb|right|A [[spectrogram]] of Bloop]]\n'''Bloop''' was an ultra-low-frequency, high amplitude underwater sound detected by the U.S. [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA) in 1997.<ref name=pmel/> By 2012, earlier speculation that the sound originated from a marine animal<ref name=\"David Wolman\">{{cite web |url= http://www.science.org.au/nova/newscientist/102ns_001.htm |title= Calls from the deep |work= New Scientist |author= David Wolman |date= 2002-06-15 |accessdate= 2012-01-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106141048/http://www.science.org.au/nova/newscientist/102ns_001.htm |archivedate=2013-01-06}}</ref> was replaced by NOAA's description of the sound as being consistent with noises generated via [[plate tectonics|non-tectonic]] [[cryoseism]]s originating from [[glacial motion|glacial movements]] such as [[ice calving]], or through [[seabed gouging by ice]].<ref name=pmel>{{cite web|title=Acoustics Monitoring Program \u2013 Icequakes (Bloop)|url=https://www.pmel.noaa.gov/acoustics/sounds/bloop.html|website=NOAA Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] / [[United States Department of Commerce]]|accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Steadman|first1=Ian|title=The Bloop Mystery Has Been Solved: It Was Never A Giant Sea Monster|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/bloop-mystery-not-solved-sort-of|website=WIRED UK|publisher=Conde Nast Publications|date=November 29, 2012}}</ref><ref name=noaa>{{cite web |last1=US Department of Commerce |first1=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |title=What is the Bloop? |url=https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/bloop.html |website=oceanservice.noaa.gov |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507010030/https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/bloop.html |archivedate=7 May 2019 |language=EN-US |date=June 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Sound profile ==\nThe sound's source was roughly triangulated to {{Coord|50|S|100|W|dim:5000000|display=inline,title}}, a remote point in the south Pacific Ocean west of the southern tip of South America. The sound was detected by the [[Equatorial Pacific Ocean autonomous hydrophone array]],<ref name=pmel/> a system of hydrophones primarily used to monitor undersea seismicity, ice noise, and marine mammal population and migration.<ref name=sosus/>{{rp|284}} This is a stand-alone system designed and built by NOAA's Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory (PMEL) to augment NOAA's use of the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] Sound Surveillance System ([[SOSUS]]), which was equipment originally designed to detect [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[submarine]]s.<ref name=sosus>{{cite thesis|last1=Di Mento|first1=John Mark|chapter=Environmental Challenges to Post-Cold War Naval Operations: The Browning of the Blue Water Battlespace|title=Beyond the Water's Edge: United States National Security & the Ocean Environment|publisher=[[Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy]], [[Tufts University]]|date=December 2006|degree=Ph.D.|location=Medford, MA|id=Document No. 3262885{{ProQuest|304741876}}|via=ProQuest Dissertations Publishing}}</ref>{{rp|255\u2013256}}\n{{Listen\n |filename     = Bloop real.ogg\n |title        = Bloop\n |description  = Bloop at 16x the original speed, from the [[NOAA]] website.\n}} According to the NOAA description, the sound \"rose\" in frequency over about one minute and was of sufficient amplitude to be heard on multiple sensors, at a range of over {{convert|5000|km|miles|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}.\n\n==Ice quake origin==\nThe NOAA Vents Program has attributed the sound to that of a large [[cryoseism]] (also known as an ice quake).<ref name=noaa/> Numerous ice quakes share similar spectrograms with Bloop, as well as the amplitude necessary to spot them despite ranges exceeding 5000&nbsp;km. This was found during the tracking of iceberg A53a as it disintegrated near [[South Georgia Island]] in early 2008. The iceberg(s) involved in generating the sound were most likely between Bransfield Straits and the Ross Sea; or possibly at Cape Adare, a well-known source of cryogenic signals.<ref name=pmel/> Sounds generated by ice quakes are easily determined through the use of hydrophones since sea water, an excellent sound channel, allows the ambient sounds generated through ice activities to travel great distances.<ref name=xie/>{{rp|5}}\n\n===Ice calving===\nIn [[ice calving]], variations result from a sound source's own motion.<ref name=xie>{{cite thesis|last1=Xie|first1=Yunbo|title=An Acoustical Study of the Properties and Behaviour of Sea Ice|degree=Ph.D.|publisher=[[University of British Columbia]]|location=Vancouver, B.C.|id=Document No. NN69775|via=ProQuest Dissertations Publishing|date=1991|url=https://open.library.ubc.ca/cIRcle/collections/ubctheses/831/items/1.0053256}}{{open access}}</ref>{{rp|55}} As oceanographer Yunbo Xie explains, the alteration of [[waveforms]] from a detected sound \"can also be caused by so-called [[angular spectrum method|angular frequency]] dependent radiation patterns associated with [[lamb waves|antisymmetric mode motion]] of the ice cover.\"<ref name=xie/>{{rp|59}}\n\n===Rubbing and ridging events within an ice floe===\nTwo processes known as rubbing and ridging are responsible for acoustical emissions similar to those from [[ice calving]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pettit|first1=Erin C.|title=Passive Underwater Acoustic Evolution of a Calving Event|journal=Annals of Glaciology|date=2012|volume=53|issue=60|pages=113\u2013122|doi=10.3189/2012aog60a137}}</ref> Rubbing involves two or more areas of compacted glacial [[ice stream|ice floes]] which are being forced together, inducing shear deformation at its edges and triggering horizontally-polarized shear waves, i. e. ''[[S-waves|SH waves]]''.<ref name=xie/>{{rp|137}} Ridging occurs when that ice bends or slides at the ridges.<ref name=xie/>{{rp|121}} According to Xie, both events will produce sound in the failure sequence (breakup) of an [[ice stream|ice floe]]:\n{{quote|\"A wave equation resulting from shear deformation will be defined in an [[ice stream|ice floe]] with the rubbing effect coupled to the floe through its boundary with the adjacent ice,\"<ref name=xie/>{{rp|137}} while \"ridging deformation(s) revealed by this event indicate that the failure process is associated with a crushing process that seals air or vacuous gaps between [[ice stream|ice floes]]. The acoustical signals emitted by this failure process are similar to those emitted from a collapsing air bubble in a fluid.\"<ref name=xie/>{{rp|121}}}}\n\n==Animal origin==\nNOAA's Christopher Fox, interviewed by David Wolman for an article in ''[[New Scientist]]'', did not believe its origin was man-made, such as a submarine or bomb, nor a familiar geological event such as a volcano or an earthquake. Fox stated that while the audio profile of Bloop does resemble that of a living creature,<ref name=\"David Wolman\" /> the source was a mystery because it would be \"far more powerful than the calls made by any animal on Earth.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=CNN.com \u2013 Tuning in to a deep sea monster \u2013 June 13, 2002|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2002/WORLD/sailing/06/13/bloop.tech/index.html|work=CNN|date=13 June 2002}}</ref> Wolman states in the article that Fox initially speculated Bloop to be [[ice calving]] in [[Antarctica]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2001/TECH/science/09/07/listening.ocean/index.html |publisher= CNN |title= Scientists tune in to sounds of the sea |date=2001-09-07 |accessdate= 2012-01-16}}</ref> but later came to believe the sound to be like that of an animal in origin:<ref name=\"David Wolman\"/>\n\n{{quotation|Fox's hunch is that the sound nicknamed Bloop is the most likely to come from some sort of animal, because its signature is a rapid variation in frequency similar to that of sounds known to be made by marine beasts. There's one crucial difference, however: in 1997 Bloop was detected by sensors up to {{convert|4800|km|miles|sigfig=2|abbr=on}} apart. That means it must be far louder than any whale noise, or any other animal noise for that matter. Is it even remotely possible that some creature bigger than any whale is lurking in the ocean depths? Or, perhaps more likely, something that is much more efficient at making sound?<ref name=hayward/>{{rp|174\u2013175}}|David Wolman}}\n\nAccording to author Philip Hayward, Wolman's speculations \"amplified Fox's 'hunch' and \u2014 through the use of the word 'likely' \u2014 opened the door for subsequent speculation as to what such an 'efficient' noise-making entity might be. Over the last decade consensus has, in fact, supported the argument that the noise is produced by ice fracturing processes.\"<ref name=hayward>{{cite book|last1=Hayward|first1=Philip|title=Making a Splash: Mermaids (and Mer-Men) in 20th and 21st Century Audiovisual Media|date=2017|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780861969258|oclc=1020857723|language=English}}</ref>{{rp|175}}\n\n== Popular culture ==\n*The Bloop was one of the phenomena investigated in the second episode of the first season of ''[[Weird or What?]]'' on Discovery Canada.\n\n*A 2012 American made-for-TV thriller produced for [[Animal Planet]] and [[Discovery Channel]] in the [[Docufiction|form of a documentary]] titled ''[[Mermaids: The Body Found]]'' used the bloop sound as evidence for the existence of [[mermaid]]s or an unknown species in the oceans.  NOAA posted a refutation on their web site.<ref name=\"Zabarenko\">{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/07/06/uk-mermaids-noaa-idUSLNE86501620120706|title=This just in: Mermaids are NOT real, U.S. agency says|last=Zabarenko|first=Deborah|date=6 July 2012|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=27 May 2014|location=Washington}}</ref>\n\n*The children's television animation [[The Deep (2015 TV series)|The Deep]] Season 1 Episode 23 finds that the sound comes from a form of sentient coral.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of unexplained sounds#NOAA (formerly unidentified)|List of formerly unidentified sounds]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.pmel.noaa.gov/acoustics/sounds/bloop.html NOAA's PMEL Acoustics Program on Icequakes (Bloop)]\n\n{{portal|Earth sciences|Water}}\n\n[[Category:1997 in science]]\n[[Category:Pacific Ocean]]\n[[Category:Snow or ice weather phenomena]]\n[[Category:Oceanography]]\n[[Category:Unidentified sounds]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Sound detected in 1997 from a non-tectonic cryoseism (ice quake)}}\n{{other uses|Bloop (disambiguation)}}\n[[File:Bloop.jpg|250px|thumb|right|A [[spectrogram]] of Bloop]]\n'''Bloop''' was an ultra-low-frequency, high amplitude underwater sound detected by the U.S. [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA) in 1997.<ref name=pmel/> By 2012, earlier speculation that the sound originated from a marine animal<ref name=\"David Wolman\">{{cite web |url= http://www.science.org.au/nova/newscientist/102ns_001.htm |title= Calls from the deep |work= New Scientist |author= David Wolman |date= 2002-06-15 |accessdate= 2012-01-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106141048/http://www.science.org.au/nova/newscientist/102ns_001.htm |archivedate=2013-01-06}}</ref> was replaced by NOAA's description of the sound as being consistent with noises generated via [[plate tectonics|non-tectonic]] [[cryoseism]]s originating from [[glacial motion|glacial movements]] such as [[ice calving]], or through [[seabed gouging by ice]].<ref name=pmel>{{cite web|title=Acoustics Monitoring Program \u2013 Icequakes (Bloop)|url=https://www.pmel.noaa.gov/acoustics/sounds/bloop.html|website=NOAA Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] / [[United States Department of Commerce]]|accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Steadman|first1=Ian|title=The Bloop Mystery Has Been Solved: It Was Never A Giant Sea Monster|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/bloop-mystery-not-solved-sort-of|website=WIRED UK|publisher=Conde Nast Publications|date=November 29, 2012}}</ref><ref name=noaa>{{cite web |last1=US Department of Commerce |first1=National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration |title=What is the Bloop? |url=https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/bloop.html |website=oceanservice.noaa.gov |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507010030/https://oceanservice.noaa.gov/facts/bloop.html |archivedate=7 May 2019 |language=EN-US |date=June 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Sound profile ==\nThe sound's source was roughly triangulated to {{Coord|50|S|100|W|dim:5000000|display=inline,title}}, a remote point in the south Pacific Ocean west of the southern tip of South America. The sound was detected by the [[Equatorial Pacific Ocean autonomous hydrophone array]],<ref name=pmel/> a system of hydrophones primarily used to monitor undersea seismicity, ice noise, and marine mammal population and migration.<ref name=sosus/>{{rp|284}} This is a stand-alone system designed and built by NOAA's Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory (PMEL) to augment NOAA's use of the [[United States Navy|U.S. Navy]] Sound Surveillance System ([[SOSUS]]), which was equipment originally designed to detect [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[submarine]]s.<ref name=sosus>{{cite thesis|last1=Di Mento|first1=John Mark|chapter=Environmental Challenges to Post-Cold War Naval Operations: The Browning of the Blue Water Battlespace|title=Beyond the Water's Edge: United States National Security & the Ocean Environment|publisher=[[Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy]], [[Tufts University]]|date=December 2006|degree=Ph.D.|location=Medford, MA|id=Document No. 3262885{{ProQuest|304741876}}|via=ProQuest Dissertations Publishing}}</ref>{{rp|255\u2013256}}\n{{Listen\n |filename     = Bloop real.ogg\n |title        = Bloop\n |description  = Bloop at 16x the original speed, from the [[NOAA]] website.\n}} According to the NOAA description, the sound \"rose\" in frequency over about one minute and was of sufficient amplitude to be heard on multiple sensors, at a range of over {{convert|5000|km|miles|sigfig=1|abbr=on}}.\n\n==Ice quake origin==\nThe NOAA Vents Program has attributed the sound to that of a large [[cryoseism]] (also known as an ice quake).<ref name=noaa/> Numerous ice quakes share similar spectrograms with Bloop, as well as the amplitude necessary to spot them despite ranges exceeding 5000&nbsp;km. This was found during the tracking of iceberg A53a as it disintegrated near [[South Georgia Island]] in early 2008. The iceberg(s) involved in generating the sound were most likely between Bransfield Straits and the Ross Sea; or possibly at Cape Adare, a well-known source of cryogenic signals.<ref name=pmel/> Sounds generated by ice quakes are easily determined through the use of hydrophones since sea water, an excellent sound channel, allows the ambient sounds generated through ice activities to travel great distances.<ref name=xie/>{{rp|5}}\n\n===Ice calving===\nIn [[ice calving]], variations result from a sound source's own motion.<ref name=xie>{{cite thesis|last1=Xie|first1=Yunbo|title=An Acoustical Study of the Properties and Behaviour of Sea Ice|degree=Ph.D.|publisher=[[University of British Columbia]]|location=Vancouver, B.C.|id=Document No. NN69775|via=ProQuest Dissertations Publishing|date=1991|url=https://open.library.ubc.ca/cIRcle/collections/ubctheses/831/items/1.0053256}}{{open access}}</ref>{{rp|55}} As oceanographer Yunbo Xie explains, the alteration of [[waveforms]] from a detected sound \"can also be caused by so-called [[angular spectrum method|angular frequency]] dependent radiation patterns associated with [[lamb waves|antisymmetric mode motion]] of the ice cover.\"<ref name=xie/>{{rp|59}}\n\n===Rubbing and