{"title_page": "Damba Zhalsarayev", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=October 2016}}\n\n'''Damba Zodbich Zhalsarayev''' ({{lang-ru|\u0414\u0430\u043c\u0431\u0430 \u0417\u043e\u0434\u0431\u0438\u0447 \u0416\u0430\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0432}}; born December 5, 1925 in [[Dodo-Gol]], [[Khorinsky District]], [[Buryat ASSR]]) wrote the [[Buryat language|Buryat]] lyrics for the [[Anthem of the Republic of Buryatia]]. He was a member of the [[Union of Soviet Writers]].<ref>[http://www.moy-ulan-ude.ru/index.php?id=12901390244ce5f590d2ec3&podrub=%CA%F3%EB%FC%F2%F3%F0%E0%20%E2%20%EB%E8%F6%E0%F5&mod=culture&pag=viewarticle/ To the 85th anniversary of the People's poet of Buryatia, Damba Zhelsarayev (in Russian)]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://soyol.ru/personas/poets-and-writers/370/ \u0416\u0430\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u0414\u0430\u043c\u0431\u0430]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWhen he was a child he worked on farms with his family. He was a student of the [[Trans-Baikal]] military infantry school in 1943 and served in the [[Second World War]] at a very young age. He fought against the [[Kwantung Army]]. After the war, he served 6 years in the border detachment of [[Kyakhtinsky District]] and was discharged in 1952. He was ranked as a [[Major]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhalsarayev, Damba}}\n[[Category:Soviet writers]]\n[[Category:Soviet propagandists]]\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n\n\n{{Russia-writer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=October 2016}}\n\n'''Damba Zodbich Zhalsarayev''' ({{lang-ru|\u0414\u0430\u043c\u0431\u0430 \u0417\u043e\u0434\u0431\u0438\u0447 \u0416\u0430\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0432}}; born December 5, 1925 in [[Dodo-Gol]], [[Khorinsky District]], [[Buryat ASSR]]) wrote the [[Buryat language|Buryat]] lyrics for the [[Anthem of the Republic of Buryatia]]. He was a member of the [[Union of Soviet Writers]].<ref>[http://www.moy-ulan-ude.ru/index.php?id=12901390244ce5f590d2ec3&podrub=%CA%F3%EB%FC%F2%F3%F0%E0%20%E2%20%EB%E8%F6%E0%F5&mod=culture&pag=viewarticle/ To the 85th anniversary of the People's poet of Buryatia, Damba Zhelsarayev (in Russian)]{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>[http://soyol.ru/personas/poets-and-writers/370/ \u0416\u0430\u043b\u0441\u0430\u0440\u0430\u0435\u0432 \u0414\u0430\u043c\u0431\u0430]</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nWhen he was a child he worked on farms with his family. He was a student of the [[Trans-Baikal]] military infantry school in 1943 and served in the [[Second World War]] at a very young age. He fought against the [[Kwantung Army]]. After the war, he served 6 years in the border detachment of [[Kyakhtinsky District]] and was discharged in 1952. He was ranked as a [[Major]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Zhalsarayev, Damba}}\n\n[[Category:Soviet writers]]\n[[Category:Soviet propagandists]]\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:Possibly living people]]\n\n\n{{Russia-writer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damba_Zhalsarayev"}
{"title_page": "Exodus Fall", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = Exodus Fall\n| image          = Exodus Fall.jpg\n| caption        = \n| director       = Ankush Kohli<br>Chad Waterhouse\n| producer       = Michael Baumgarten<br>Ankush Kohli<br>Adriana LaCorte\n| writer         = Chad Waterhouse\n| starring       = [[Rosanna Arquette]]<br>[[Jesse James (actor)|Jesse James]]<br>[[Devon Graye]]<br>[[Dee Wallace]]<br>[[Christopher Atkins]]\n| music          = Boris Zelkin\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = Oakhurst Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2011|04}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Exodus Fall''''' is a 2011 American [[drama (film and television)|drama]] [[road movie|road film]] directed by Ankush Kohli and Chad Waterhouse, and starring [[Rosanna Arquette]], [[Jesse James (actor)|Jesse James]], [[Devon Graye]], [[Dee Wallace]], and [[Christopher Atkins]].\n\n==Plot==\nSet in 1974, the film centers on three siblings from [[Texas]] \u2014 Kenneth ([[Jesse James (actor)|Jesse James]]), Charlotte (Adrien Finkel), and Dana Minor ([[Devon Graye]]) \u2014 who are left living with their abusive, alcoholic mother Marilyn ([[Rosanna Arquette]]) after their father's death. Marilyn commits Dana, who is [[autism|autistic]], to an institution, allowing doctors to perform medical experiments on him. Kenneth and Charlotte break their younger brother out of the asylum, and the three siblings set out on a [[road trip]], intending to travel from Texas to their grandmother's home in [[Oregon]]. They are joined by a [[hippie]] named Travis (Alexander Carroll).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/exodus-fall/5428|title=Exodus Fall|date=17 April 2011|accessdate=12 December 2013|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|author=Andrew Schenker}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|title=Exodus-Fall (2011)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/465339/Exodus-Fall/