.jpg\n| caption        = \n| director       = Ankush Kohli<br>Chad Waterhouse\n| producer       = Michael Baumgarten<br>Ankush Kohli<br>Adriana LaCorte\n| writer         = Chad Waterhouse\n| starring       = [[Rosanna Arquette]]<br>[[Jesse James (actor)|Jesse James]]<br>[[Devon Graye]]<br>[[Dee Wallace]]<br>[[Christopher Atkins]]\n| music          = Boris Zelkin\n| cinematography = \n| editing        = \n| distributor    = Oakhurst Pictures\n| released       = {{Film date|2011|04}}\n| runtime        =\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n}}\n'''''Exodus Fall''''' is a 2011 American drama road film directed by Ankush Kohli and Chad Waterhouse, and starring [[Rosanna Arquette]], [[Jesse James (actor)|Jesse James]], [[Devon Graye]], [[Dee Wallace]], and [[Christopher Atkins]].\n\n==Plot==\nSet in 1974, the film centers on three siblings from [[Texas]] \u2014 Kenneth ([[Jesse James (actor)|Jesse James]]), Charlotte (Adrien Finkel), and Dana Minor ([[Devon Graye]]) \u2014 who are left living with their abusive, alcoholic mother Marilyn ([[Rosanna Arquette]]) after their father's death. Marilyn commits Dana, who is [[autism|autistic]], to an institution, allowing doctors to perform medical experiments on him. Kenneth and Charlotte break their younger brother out of the asylum, and the three siblings set out on a [[road trip]], intending to travel from Texas to their grandmother's home in [[Oregon]]. They are joined by a [[hippie]] named Travis (Alexander Carroll).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/film/review/exodus-fall/5428|title=Exodus Fall|date=17 April 2011|accessdate=12 December 2013|work=[[Slant Magazine]]|author=Andrew Schenker}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Dargis|first=Manohla|title=Exodus-Fall (2011)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/465339/Exodus-Fall/overview|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Gold|first=Daniel M|title=Exodus Fall (2011)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/20